### Complete Lean Proof

```lean4
theorem infinity_of_primes₁ (S : Finset ℕ) (h : ∀ q ∈ S, Nat.Prime q):
  ∃ (p : ℕ), Nat.Prime p ∧ p ∉ S := by
  have h₁ : ∃ (p : ℕ), Nat.Prime p ∧ p ∉ S := by
    let n := 1 + ∏ q ∈ S, q
    let p := n.minFac
    use p
    have hp : Nat.Prime p := Nat.minFac_prime <| Nat.ne_of_gt <| lt_add_of_pos_right 1
      (Finset.prod_pos fun q hq ↦ Prime.pos <| h q hq)
    refine ⟨hp, ?_⟩
    by_contra a
    have h_p_div_prod : p ∣ ∏ q ∈ S, q := dvd_prod_of_mem (fun (i : ℕ) ↦ i) a
    have h_p_div_diff : p ∣ n - ∏ q ∈ S, q := dvd_sub (minFac_dvd n) h_p_div_prod
    have h_p_div_one : p ∣ 1 := by
      have h₁ : n - ∏ q ∈ S, q = 1 := by
        have h₂ : ∏ q ∈ S, q ≥ 0 := by
          apply Finset.prod_nonneg
          intro x _
          exact Nat.zero_le x
        have h₃ : n = 1 + ∏ q ∈ S, q := rfl
        have h₄ : n - ∏ q ∈ S, q = 1 := by
          omega
        exact h₄
      rw [h₁] at h_p_div_diff
      exact h_p_div_diff
    exact Nat.Prime.not_dvd_one hp h_p_div_one
  exact h₁
``` 

This proof directly translates the steps of Euclid's proof into Lean. The `have` statement at the beginning is essentially the same as the theorem statement, and the rest of the proof is the detailed construction that we outlined. The contradiction arises because no prime divides 1, which is a fundamental property of primes. The Lean proof uses the `minFac` function to find the smallest prime factor of `n`, which is sufficient since we only need one new prime not in the set `S`. 

